        title: 'Typing the tone of your voice',
        text: "Some language rules on the Internet depend on a typed-in tone of voice. A clear example is the use of all caps to signal emphasis, strong feeling, or even shouting. Emphatic caps may look like an Internet quirk, but the practice goes back well before the web. A message written in all caps, like I LOVE YOU, tells the reader that the tone is happy or even happier than usual.\n\nEmphatic caps are a clean way to express strong feeling and have survived the move from letter writing to the Internet era.\n\nRepeating letters is another old informal writing tool that works especially well for emotional words like yay or no. Another way to show tone is the sarcasm tilde. The tilde is a punctuation mark that signals sarcasm in the absence of physical cues like a raised eyebrow or a wry smile. When other punctuation marks fall short, the tilde keeps sarcasm subtle and context-aware online.\n\nPeriods at the end of utterances, lengthened letters, all caps, irony punctuation, minimal punctuation, and capital letters paired with line breaks all belong to the system of typed tone, and the system works. Still, a need arose to express thoughts with more accuracy, and that is where emoji stepped in.\n\nGretchen McCulloch has noted that repeating letters is another way to express emphasis online.",
